column38: It was helpful to speak my thoughts in the first task as it helped to refine my thoughts but it felt like a hurdle which slowed me down during the second task.  Sometimes the robot kept saying things like aha or so which sometimes distracted me. But it was nice to describe it to someone as it well responsive to my speech.

It felt good in a way that you where talking to something that listen to you but I think that the robot should speak more, Interact more and that it should react more to my answers so that it would be more like if I was talking to a real person and not just a robot.
The robot didn't respond to my thoughts. I wasn't very interactive. But the design made it look cool and a bit human-like.

The sounds meant to make it seem like it was responding/paying attention would interrupt me mid sentence, which broke immersion. The voice was obviously robotic, but soothing. It worked well for giving the instructions. I felt more aware of the camera and recording than of the robot and mostly tuned it out. It might actually be more helpful to talk to something totally inanimate, that doesn't respond. With the robot I was never sure when or how it would react.
column40: It felt like I was focusing a lot on detailing all the thoughts I had out loud instead of only talking out loud during a particularly tricky spot. And normally I would use a pen and paper for some of the problems. So in these two ways my behavior during the study was likely different from natural rubberducking.

column38: It accompanies you but he seems not understanding me.

It felt like I was not speaking with someone but to them. There was little acknowledgement of things I said which made it a one way discussion. It felt like the effort of speaking for the robot slowed down my progress as my train of thought wanted to run faster than I was managing to speak. Had the robot been an actual person I would have been even slower as I would have taken more time to make sure my words were being understood.

I think I mostly ignored the robots presence focusing more on my task and my own thoughts. Sometimes it was hard to phrase my thoughts correctly which distracted me from the task a bit. But on the other hand I really felt s connection to the robot and it felt comforting to have hi  in the room. I think that talking aloud to the robot ot made the problem of solving the task more enjoyable and made me feel more secure with myself.
It was weird. The only responses he gave were agreeing to my thoughts even so sometimes it didn't make any sense.
Positive
Calm and stable and confident

The robot responded "yeah" in the middle of my sentences, which made me feel like it wasn't listening to me. But I like how it asked me to talk about my favourite day of the week, which was a good way to build rapport. But then it responded "interesting opinions" which was a bit weird and out of my expectations. But overall I felt like the robot had a presence, but it didn't disturb me a lot, more of like I know someone was there.

column40: Talking to a rubber duck seems to increase the self doubt in me. While speaking there is an inherent critical criterion. This helps find errors in thought process. If used at all times however, it would be exhausting.
It was harder to think aloud in the first task
I like to write down my thoughts rather than think outloud because that distracts me from the task and then I can't think properly
Felt like bot was not there
The duck was looking at the door. So in the end, everytime I looked at it I thought you were coming when the time was up. Also because it was too far away. I felt endorsement from the microphone

column38: The occasional um and ah sounded natural but never really felt natural. I liked the eye movements of the robot and the blinks looked like that of a human beings. The robot didn't help me in concentrating

+ it felt like teaching or explaining stuff to a stranger. I felt responsible to explain the tasks in a way that the robot can understand
- I couldn't tell or had no time really to check the robot's facial expression that would give me a hint if he really understood what I was trying to explain

I did not ask any questions, so it was more of a description of what I was doing, for which I usually expect some kind of reassurance. The robot did exactly that, by reacting in a neutral manner or positively, which I appreciated. On the other hand, it felt like the intensity of the verbal approval did not match the sensibility of the statements and assumptions I was making, so at some point I felt that the robot does not really process what I am saying - but it was still nice to feel certain approval.
Quite interesting to speak and communicate on the positive side,  whereas on negative side it's pre-programmed I think
I am not afraid of being judged by robots. Positive thing it is very sensitive to my speaking. Negative thing could be he can not smile around.
It's fine because it is listening to you, but it is not having a real conversation about what you are saying
He had badly timed gasps in the middle of my sentences, which was annoying. But he was calm that was comforting
column40: Cheers

column38: I felt it was listening to me but he did not reply back just I felt its approval.
The robot speaks in a less natural way, so I ignored it somehow and talked to the air. The robot told me when to start and end clearly. So it was helpful.
column40: I don't know clearly the difference of how and what for solving a task. For me they are close to each other.

column38: Talking to Alex was fine, but it sometimes interrupted me with its "uhue", "yes", "I understand". Also the eyemovment felt unnatural. It had a pleasant calm voice.

It was nice to have around, but it didn't make much impact and was very quiet. Maybe I talked to it the wrong way? Maybe I should've looked at it more or asking questions but I knew it couldn't help me
It was odd, something new, but after a while it is like talking to a stranger that wants to know what you are thinking in order to improve or solve a task

The robot was welcoming and calming, and friendly feels good to talk to it. But it seems not understand me when I asked a question if I need to read the questions aloud, and the robot gives me reactions when I said something, but it feels a little bit different from real people, it feels a bit fake, maybe because it didn't understand my last question

column40: English is not my first language so I feel like that impacted my experience,  maybe it would have felt more rewarding speaking aloud if I spoke in Swedish,
It was hard to think aloud before understanding the problem myself first. It helped to read quietly and getting a basic grasp of the task before trying to explain.

column38: The robot provided poorly timed feedback and did not feel to closely connected to what was said. It provided conversational support but not naturally. If I came to a strong conclusion, the robot would often do nothing but when I just asked myself a question it would say "that's right" or nod. Very awkward
column40: Fun experience!

column38: Speaking to the robo was fun. He looked interested in hearing my thoughts. Blinking of his eyes gave me feeling that he was genuinely listening. One negative aspect would be that he doesn't really understand if I have finished talking or not or it could be said as he interrupted me before I finished talking.
The nodding was a good touch but it was not related with what I was saying. Felt kind of random. When I directly interacted with it, asking if it is finished, it didn't respond.
It was more like talking to myself, definately helped more in the second task. The robot felt aloof and mildly interested in what was going on.
column40: Where was the rubber duck?

column38:
Positive: the voice and face are nice and calm, the robot feels natural.
Negative: the eyes are looking away, there is no eye contact, even punctual and I felt it made me consider it more like an object than a person. The small replies when I was talking were with some delay or unexpected pace which would not happen with another person and was not helping in the thinking process.

Really interesting. The robot was friendly and seemed to understand what I was saying. Moreover, he gave the right instructions and it was easy to follow him. I liked his eyes. I think there were no negative aspects.
I felt good and comfort with robot. However, talking while solving distracted me.
column40: No

column38: I didn't  see the robot while I was solving the exercises, I just saw he "reacted" when I was frustrated and said something,  but I don't know if it was a coincidence. I was very curious  about  the robot, but I kinda forget  about it  when I was focused on the tasks

A little bit awkward as it felt like talking to myself but I was supposed to feel like I was talking to a robot and that made me feel a little bit uncomfortable. I also think that it feels that way because I don't feel like the robot is going to understand you and rather they analyse you so it's not an horizontal interaction.

The robot was emitting noise of agreement at random moments, sometimes when I was speaking so I felt interrupted. The frequency of its reactions did not match my intensity of thinking (finally finding an answer for ex), so the interaction felt very artificial. I don't feel like having an interactive robot was an improvement compared to an inanimate object. But it was not in the uncanny valley so it was pretty nice to interact with
column40: I felt slow thinking in english rather than in my mother tongue

column38: The robot did a good job with expressions but I felt little strange to talk to a robot because it is the first time I was talking to a machine
I didn't speak much mainly expressed my thoughts. But the robot is responsive however, can't replace a human interaction as I didnt get the emotional feedback.
column40: The robot looks a bit scary. But seems like a smart robot.

column38: Sometimes Alex spoke when I didn't finished my sentence which was a bit unnatural, else it was helping to speak out loud and to have a sort of approval
The face was pretty human like, I liked that it give some responses like hmmm and nodding (could have been more frequent though)
Weird, felt like I was taking a test at aperture. It had calm speech, but it didnt feel like it actually cared what I had to say.
column40: This was fun!

column38: I found myself talking to myself more than the robot. Part of me knew it would provide no feedback, so after a while I almost zoned it out.
column40: The two types of exercise are very different. I would have liked to separate my answers for the Thinking Aloud feedback section.

column38: It was ok
It was really awkward as if I am being watched by someone creepy, the positive  thing is that howmrobots can operate by AI.
column40: None

column38: I realised that it was nodding but only from the corner of my eye as I was focusing on the iPad and task instead, in all honesty I only paid attention to it at the beginning of each task, then I was more in my own headspace and thought process. I was not uncomfortable with it being there, it felt very similar to being in a room with a stranger actually, it was just not natural for me to address it.
Its behaviour and reactions lacked emotion but it seemed engaged in the conversation and was listening carefully and answering accordingly.
I don't know how well it understands me so it rather felt like I was talking to the camera,era or recording

Positive: it tells you when to start 

Negative: it responded "emm" as if it was listening but at the wrong pace, often jumped in when I was still talking aloud, which is not very common between conversations with human beings unless they want to cut in and say something on their own. It is a little annoying. Also I am not a fan of the robotic voice,  I think having a human being doing a voice over and use their voice is better.
Strange in one moment when he started saying "mm" randomly without me saying very useful stuff or stuff at all. Otherwise he said it in correct times mostly

It felt more natural to speak out loud with the robot present. It was a fun experience talking with the robot. I felt more confident talking to the robot than with e.g. a human since I felt like it would not judge me for what I was saying. I liked that it was mostly quiet during the task because it helped me think but it would also be nice to get some response to what I was saying.

I am easily distracted by needing to talk out loud what I am thinking, and the robots face is quite creepy, I just pretend there is someone next to me and I am talking to him. I like how it nods sometimes.

At the beginning he nodded to some of my reasoning, and even thought it was a bit of time it still felt good, afterwile I didnt hear hi, again and it was a bit like talking to myself. Overall I liked he didnt excessively agreed and nodded with my resentments but I would have expected a bit more interaction

The robot was simply talking without emotions. It feels like I am still talking to an object.

However, the robot can still provide some responses at sometimes

It felt less lonely in the room and it alleviated some panic of time constraints. His facial responses are quite convincing that he offers human like company. 1) But sometimes he interjected at a thought, which felt misplaced and pre-recorded. 2) I talk out loud in general, and I'm not super polite with my computers. But I felt the need to explain to Alex, to not take it personally. Very human like robots can take that space away maybe?

If you want to compare the real human, I think his face , voice,  movement are quiet similar. That's really amazing.  But there is no true eye contact.  At first,  he said he is Alex, and I  immediately say my name. He is still talking.  At that moment,  I know he is robot  and no much intellen6

Nice to have something representing an objective observer, however I would like the feedback/interactions where it asks questions when something is unclear or if I'm not describing something clearly enough. It was quite quiet overall.
The robots facial expressions creeped me out to some extent, I'd rather stick to simple questions or tasks as with siri rather than having a full conversation with a robot

Feel good and nature when talking with the robot.  The robot is interactive when it comes to communication. It has a good physical response when talking. However, I feel that I didn't get very much meaningful information from the robot.
column40: The big camera beside and under the robot makes me feel a little bit under nature

column38: I did not talk to him I am sorry If i miss understood a part of the task, i talked mostly to myself, i felt more uneasy with the camera and feeling to be looked at and assessed and hence uncomfortable and stressed (hence not reflecting very well) than really cared about the robot

It was nice to have something to talk to on my thought process, be it a rubber duck or a robot... The robot gave verbal confirmation like "yes", indicating that it tried to listen, but most of the confirmation happened at very strange places, showing that it didn't understand. It felt like talking to someone who isn't listening but I had to get the conversation going... A bit like an awkward lecture where you ask students for questions and the room just goes silent...

At first when it asked me about myself, there seemed to be some interaction. But later when I was solving the problems, all it was saying was "yes" or "hmm". But I did not expect it to say more because its role is just a rubber duck.
The robots face was so distracting, I wanted just to talk to the robot

column40: If there would be some interation with duck, it could be great
